<article>

  <p>
    Desire stops feeding fantasy. Ill-will loses its heat. Fog thins. Restlessness
    settles enough for the object to hold. Doubt stops arguing with the method long
    enough to look. What arrives next is often relief — and then, almost as fast, a
    quieter form of the same problem: wanting the relief to stay.
  </p>

  <p>
    The
    <a href="/concepts/five-hindrances/"><span class="pali" data-pali="nīvaraṇa" data-en="hindrance">nīvaraṇas</span></a>
    page is about recognising the five covers that obstruct stillness and clear
    seeing. This page is about the gap after one of them loosens. That gap is not a
    certificate. It is a change of conditions. How it is met often decides whether the
    quieter mind becomes usable — or just another pleasant state to chase.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>When the Water Stops Moving</h2>

  <p>
    Sit long enough and the texture can shift mid-hour. A fantasy that owned attention
    simply stops recruiting. An old argument stops reheating. The body that felt half
    asleep becomes ordinarily awake. Scanning slows. The mind that was bargaining with
    the method becomes willing, for a stretch, to keep looking. None of that requires
    drama. Conditions change, and the sit becomes different.
  </p>

  <p>
    What remains is often brightness, sudden room, a sense that there is space again.
    The Buddha’s water similes still fit: dye that stops being stirred, boiling that
    settles, weeds that part, wind that dies down, mud that falls. The water does not
    become something else. It becomes clearer.
  </p>

  <p>
    That clearer field is ordinary — and temporary. What has loosened can tighten
    again before the sit ends. Worth holding lightly: a good stretch of mind is
    information about conditions, not proof of a new identity.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Absence Is Not Arrival</h2>

  <p>
    The common misreading is to treat the first clear patch as the thing practice was
    for. It is not
    <span class="pali" data-pali="jhāna" data-en="meditative absorption">jhāna</span>.
    Absorption has its own factors and depth. A hindrance falling away is often only
    the precondition — the mind no longer blocked in that particular way. Nor is the
    relief liberation. Temporary absence of an obstruction is valuable and ordinary.
    Confusing the two hardens into pride when the quiet holds, and into
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vicikicchā" data-en="doubt">vicikicchā</span>
    when the next difficult sit arrives.
  </p>

  <p>
    Of course the mind wants to score the moment. “I got past that.” Ownership invites
    comparison and disappointment. The hindrance was never a personal failure in the
    way the mind wants to prosecute it, and its passing is not a personal victory in
    the way the mind wants to cash it. Conditions shifted. Attention can notice that
    without turning it into a story about who one has become.
  </p>

  <p>
    The distinction that matters is simple: knowing a cover is absent is not the same
    as having finished the work those covers were interrupting. Clear water is not yet
    clear seeing put to use.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>How the Mind Recaptures Clarity</h2>

  <p>
    The gap after a hindrance dissolves is fertile — and easily mishandled. Watch what
    happens in the first minutes of ease.
  </p>

  <p>
    Attention often turns from the meditation object to the pleasant absence of
    obstruction. The calm becomes a new form of
    <span class="pali" data-pali="kāmacchanda" data-en="sensual desire">kāmacchanda</span>
    — desire for the feeling of having dissolved desire. The grip itself tends to
    recreate agitation. Wanting and not-wanting do not need an external object; a quiet
    sit is enough.
  </p>

  <p>
    Or the mind, sensing one quality gone, scans for the next problem to fix. Useful
    investigation turns into restless productivity — close kin to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="uddhacca" data-en="restlessness">uddhacca</span>.
    The sit becomes a cleanup project. Relief lasts only long enough to fuel the next
    hunt.
  </p>

  <p>
    Consider the absurdity: a hindrance loosens, and within a few breaths the mind is
    either clutching the calm, congratulating itself, or looking for fresh trouble. The
    obstruction left. The habit of interference did not. Meeting that habit without
    feeding it is already closer to the path’s non-grasping than any peak the quiet
    might seem to promise.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>The Knowledge Easy to Skip</h2>

  <p>
    The
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/"><span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">Satipaṭṭhāna</span></a>
    teaching on the hindrances does not stop at “present” and “absent.” It also asks
    for knowledge of how an unarisen hindrance comes to arise, how an arisen one is
    abandoned, and — most often skipped — how an abandoned one does not arise again.
    Relief makes that last item feel optional. Training makes it the point.
  </p>

  <p>
    Nothing here demands that the quiet become permanent. What it asks is simpler: notice
    the causes that actually helped. Naming without a character trial. A little more
    energy in the posture. Softening the story that was feeding ill-will. Returning to
    the object with less demand that the sit perform. Cause and effect, seen early enough
    that the next arising meets less identification — that is the fifth knowledge in
    ordinary clothes.
  </p>

  <p>
    The traditional orientations —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="asubha" data-en="unattractiveness">asubha</span>
    for desire,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="mettā" data-en="loving-kindness">mettā</span>
    for ill-will,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="viriya" data-en="energy">viriya</span>
    for dullness,
    <span class="pali" data-pali="passaddhi" data-en="tranquility">passaddhi</span>
    for restlessness, investigation for doubt — are not emergency tools only. They also
    protect a clearer field: they keep supporting conditions in view without turning
    protection into another fight.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    “He knows how an unarisen hindrance comes to arise; he knows how an arisen
    hindrance comes to be abandoned; he knows how an abandoned hindrance does
    not arise again in the future.”
    <cite>— MN 10, Satipaṭṭhāna Sutta (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <hr>

  <h2>Leave the Gap Ordinary</h2>

  <p>
    When a cover lifts, continue. Breath, body, chosen object — ordinary attention in a
    mind with a little more room. The invitation is not to manufacture a better state
    from the dissolution. It is to stop treating the quieter field as either a trophy or
    a threat.
  </p>

  <p>
    Using the quiet as leverage — hoping, under the surface, that ease will lock in —
    is still grasping. Meeting the same quiet as a condition that has arisen and will
    pass is something else. One keeps the old habit dressed as progress. The other lets
    attention stay with what is actually here.
  </p>

  <p>
    If
    <span class="pali" data-pali="samādhi" data-en="unification">samādhi</span>
    deepens from there, fine. If it does not, also fine. What matters at this threshold
    is remaining present while the mind is less obstructed — seeing the object, the body,
    and the mind-state itself without needing the relief to become a story about progress.
  </p>

  <p>
    Covers arise, are known, loosen, and return. That rhythm is not failure. It is the
    training field. A mind that can meet the dissolving without clutching is already
    rehearsing the non-grasping the path aims at. The water clears. Then sit with what
    is visible.
  </p>

</article>
